# Use Radix Theme Components

When building UI in this project, **always use Radix Theme components when a suitable one exists**. Do not use raw HTML elements or custom wrappers for things Radix provides.

## Layout & structure
- Use `Box`, `Container`, `Section`, `Flex`, `Grid`, `Inset` instead of raw `div` (use `Box asChild` with semantic elements like `header`/`footer` when you need the tag).
- Use `Text`, `Heading`, `Code`, `Kbd`, `Link`, `Strong`, `Em` instead of raw `p`, `h1`â€“`h6`, `code`, `a`, etc.

## Interactive & forms
- Use `Button`, `IconButton` for actions.
- Use `TextField`, `TextArea`, `Select`, `Checkbox`, `Switch`, `Slider`, etc. for form controls.
- Use `Card` for card-style containers.

## Feedback & overlay
- Use `Separator` for dividers instead of styled `hr` or border divs.
- Use Radix `Dialog`, `Popover`, `Tooltip`, `DropdownMenu`, etc. when adding overlays or dialogs.

## What not to do
- Do not add per-component style overrides that duplicate or override Radix theme (e.g. avoid `color="gray"` or `highContrast` on one button and not another unless the design explicitly requires it).
- Do not use inline styles for colors/fonts that the theme already provides; rely on Theme provider and `globals.css` tokens.
- Do not introduce another UI library for components that Radix Theme already provides.

## Example
```tsx
// Prefer
<Flex gap="3" align="center">
  <Code size="3">npx omega-code</Code>
  <Button size="3" variant="soft">Copy</Button>
</Flex>

// Avoid
<div style={{ display: 'flex', gap: 12 }}>
  <code className="...">npx omega-code</code>
  <button className="...">Copy</button>
</div>
```
